Exploratory analysis: Formal procedures

This exploratory analysis focuses on the Formal procedures dimension and includes various data summaries in table and graphical forms. The dimension is concpetualised as Political vs. Legal.

List of items

The Formal Procedures scale has been constructed on the basis of these items:

Item Question
13 Is there a formal admissibility check?
14 Who decides about the formal admissibility?
15 Is there a legal remedy against the decision on formal admissibility?
16 Who decides about the claim for remedy in the formal admissibility procedure?
17 Who can initiate the formal remedy procedure (state actor - initiator - anyone)?
18 Does the formal admissibility procedure take place before the signature collection?
20 Do participants have a right to be heard in the formal admissibility procedure?
21 Is there an evidentiary procedure in the formal admissibility procedure?
22 Are the legal consequences of the formal admissibility procedures binding?
23 Is invalidity the legal consequence of formal inadmissibility?

Checking data

Two most important points:

  1. Formal procedures seem to have 2 filter items, 13 and 15. These are left out of subsequent analysis.

  2. For now, Item 18, on formal admissibility before signature collection, is EXCLUDED since it does not apply to most number of instruments.

Country check

Another aspect worth checking is the Country impact. The visualisation below allows us to check how Country affects Formal prohibitions. It is organised by the items on Y axis and the Countries on the X axis. The bubble represent the count (i.e., how many prohibitions a country has per item). This is related to the number of instruments a country has; thus a country with 5, will have a maximum number of 5 prohibitions.

Visualising these country effects allows us to see whether a particular country is driving the count for a particular Item.

Matrix of ‘Legal’ value counts for each item organised by country
